         <abstract>
            <p>The <foreign xml:lang="gez">Gize ṣalot</foreign>  is a version of the <ref type="work" corresp="LIT1961Mashaf">Maṣḥafa saʿātāt</ref>, a Church 
               service made up of psalms, biblical readings and hymns. 
               However, it is actually a genre of its own, a <foreign xml:lang="gez">Gize ṣalot</foreign> for the use of hermits (<foreign xml:lang="gez">ባሕታዊያን፡</foreign>) 
               and recluses <foreign xml:lang="gez">የዘጉ፡</foreign>.
               <bibl>
                  <ptr target="bm:Taft1986Liturgy"/> 
                  <citedRange unit="page">270</citedRange>
               </bibl> follow the Ethiopian distribution of the psalter.</p>
            <p>The three other types of <foreign xml:lang="gez">Maṣḥafa saʿātāt</foreign> identified by  <bibl>
                  <ptr target="bm:Taft1986Liturgy"/>
                  <citedRange unit="page">266</citedRange>
               </bibl> are: </p>
            <p> 
               <ref type="work" corresp="LIT2230Saatat"/>: the Coptic Saʿātāt;</p>
            <p> 
               <ref type="work" corresp="LIT3575Mashaf"/>: the Saʿātāt of <persName ref="PRS4709Giyorgis">Giyorgis of Saglā</persName>, 
               which replaced the <ref type="work" corresp="LIT2230Saatat"/>:  and is presently in use in Ethiopia and Eritrea;</p>
            <p>
               <ref type="work" corresp="LIT3576Saatat"/>:  a Saʿātāt that includes the entire Psalter in the daily pensum;</p>
